'''Faciendum''' is an English term derived from [[Latin]], meaning "something to do" or "something that must be done."

Unlike English, Latin has a grammatical sense that indicates obligation, known as the [[gerundive]] sense. In Latin this is expressed with the suffixes -nda -dnus -dnum, the [[gender]] being female, male and [[neuter]], respectively. "Facere" is the Latin infinitive of the verb "to do", therefore when combined with the neuter gender (indicating that that it is a ''thing'' to be done as opposed to a ''person'') the word faciendum (pl. ''facienda'') is generated.